@startuml
!theme plain

title **BDD Test Architecture with Cucumber + POM**

' Components
package "1. Feature File (*.feature)" as FEATURE #LightBlue
package "2. Page Object (POM)" as POM #LightGreen
package "3. Step Definitions" as STEPS #LightYellow
package "4. World (Context)" as WORLD #LightCoral
package "5. Hooks (Setup/Teardown)" as HOOKS #LightGray

' Relationships
FEATURE --> STEPS : "describes scenarios (Gherkin)"
STEPS --> POM : "use high-level methods"
STEPS --> WORLD : "access page/driver via World"
WORLD --> POM : "instantiates Page Objects"
HOOKS --> WORLD : "initializes/cleans up World"

' Explanatory notes
note right of FEATURE
  **Example:** login.feature
  Contains scenarios in
  Given/When/Then format. It is the
  executable specification.
end note

note right of POM
  **Example:** LoginPage.ts
  Encapsulates locators and
  page actions.
  Methods like `loginWithValidCredentials()`
end note

note right of STEPS
  **Example:** login.steps.ts
  Maps each Gherkin step to
  an action on the Page Object.
  Delegates UI logic.
end note

note right of WORLD
  **Example:** world.ts
  Shared context between steps.
  Stores `page`, `browser`,
  Page Object instances.
end note

note right of HOOKS
  **Example:** hooks.ts
  Defines `@Before` and `@After`.
  Initializes World (driver, page)
  and cleans up after each scenario.
end note

' Execution flow
note bottom of HOOKS
  **Flow:**
  1. Hooks run `@Before` → create World.
  2. Cucumber reads Feature and executes Steps.
  3. Steps use World and Page Objects.
  4. On completion, `@After` releases resources.
end note

@enduml
